message_content: Yin Hao: Mom, how has everything been at home lately? The weather is starting to get hot.

Yin Hao: Received. I'm in charge of bringing water and my coffee. I've been taking drip coffee bags for camping lately—they have more flavor than instant coffee, and are less hassle than bringing beans. Just boil some water and pour it over.
Gao Zhiyuan: Alright, that's quite particular. I thought you'd bring the three-in-one kind. What brand of drip coffee is good?

Yin Hao: The three-in-one coffee is too sweet, like a beverage. I can't get used to it now. I often buy a type of Yunnan small-grain coffee in drip bags, medium roast, not sour, with just the right balance of bitterness and aroma. Having a cup outdoors in the morning really wakes me up.
Wang Lei: Haozi, wanna play games together tonight? Engineer Liu seemed a bit off today; he made a small mistake in programming and got a couple of words from Master Sun.
Yin Hao: Sure, I'll be online at eight. What's up with Engineer Liu? He's usually quite meticulous.

Wang Lei: Ah, it's not about work. He was venting to me at noon, saying that the landlord of the apartment he rents in Kunshan suddenly wants to sell it and gave him a month to move out. He's been stressed about finding a new place, spending every day looking at apartments until his head hurts. Probably hasn't been resting well.
Yin Hao: So sudden? One month is quite tight. What's his budget? Should I ask around our neighborhood to see if there's anything for rent?

Wang Lei: That sounds great! His budget is about the same as before, around three thousand, and he just needs to be close to the subway. Could you help ask around? We can discuss the details more in the game tonight.
Gao Zhiyuan: Haozi, want to go fishing this weekend? Brother Wu says the fishing at Dianshan Lake has been pretty good lately.
Yin Hao: Sure, Saturday morning? By the way, I've recently gotten into pour-over coffee—having a cup in the morning keeps me energized all day. I just bought a beginner's set.
Gao Zhiyuan: Sure, you're really into the finer details. What kind of beans do you usually drink? I've heard that anaerobic fermentation is all the rage these days, with a really strong fruity aroma.

Yin Hao: I've tried anaerobic fermentation; the flavor is intense, but I find it a bit "dirty" and not to my taste. Sun-dried beans have a nice sweetness, but occasionally, there are off-flavors. After trying various methods, I still prefer washed coffee the most, especially Ethiopian ones. They have a clean taste and bright acidity, almost like drinking fruit juice—very refreshing.
Gao Zhiyuan: Got it, you prefer the refreshing route. Alright, meet at the usual spot at 6 a.m. on Saturday, and don’t forget to bring your "spiritual juice."

Yin Hao, this is Liu Zhiqiang. Regarding the alloy trial processing data we discussed in the break area the other day, could you send me the detailed parameters? I’d like to review them in advance to prepare for tomorrow’s discussion.

Zhang Wei: Haozi, any new song recommendations at KTV lately? We're still stuck singing the same old tunes over here.
Yin Hao: Haha, I haven't been to KTV much lately. My music taste has changed even when listening at home.
Zhang Wei: What's changed? Didn't you used to love listening to Jay Chou and JJ Lin?
Yin Hao: Nowadays, after returning from an evening run or while studying for exams, I enjoy playing some pure music, like piano pieces. It’s incredibly calming and makes my mind feel clearer.

Mom: Haohao, your uncle has been feeling a bit down lately. Give him a call and chat when you have time.

message_content: Liu Zhiqiang: Brother Lei, is the plan for tonight settled? Shall we proceed as discussed at noon? Should I give the master a heads-up first?
Yin Hao: Jie, don't forget what we talked about at breakfast.
Yin Tao: Haozi, are you busy? I just got off the phone with Sister Wenwen, and I have some good news.
Yin Hao: Just got off work, what's the good news? Did she change jobs?

Yin Tao: No, she didn't change jobs. She got promoted! Her company held an internal competition before the New Year, and she secured the position of design supervisor. She'll be taking up the role after the New Year.
Yin Hao: Impressive! Wenwen must be getting a significant raise then. What about her and that boyfriend of hers, any updates?

Yin Tao: Haha, you asked the right question. She said she plans to get married this National Day, and both families have already discussed it. We'll probably both have to go to Hangzhou for the wedding banquet then.
Wang Lei: Haozi, did you go see the apartment over the weekend? How did you feel about that new development in Songjiang?
Yin Hao: I've seen it. It's close to the subway, and the commercial facilities are good. But something feels missing—it's too bustling, with buildings packed closely together.
Wang Lei: What else do you want? A school district? You don't have children right now.
Yin Hao: Not a school district. Actually, I've always thought it would be best if the house were near a large park, or by a river or a lake.

Yin Hao: After work or on weekends, I can just step out to go for a run or a walk. The environment is quiet, and it lifts my mood. In contrast, where I currently rent, although it’s convenient, I have to make a special trip to the sports center just to go for a run.
Yin Hao: Bro, what have you been up to lately? I saw you posted a location update in Suzhou Industrial Park on your social media.
Yin Tao: Haha, you caught me. I've been looking at houses in Suzhou recently and just settled on one in Mudu, Wuzhong District, which is close to where I work.
Yin Hao: Sure thing, bro! Congratulations! Is the down payment pressure heavy?

Yin Tao: Not bad, saved up for a few years and got a little support from my parents. Planning to start the renovation in May next year, so you can come to Suzhou and help me brainstorm ideas then. I’m thinking of installing a smart home system, the kind with voice control for lights and curtains—seems pretty convenient.
Yin Hao: No problem! I'm not very knowledgeable about smart homes, but I can definitely help you move things and supervise the work.
Gao Zhiyuan: Haozi, my car is about to hit 60,000 kilometers, and I'm planning to do a major maintenance. How's your car doing?
Yin Hao: My car is still okay, just over 40,000 yuan. It's just that I feel the power is a bit sluggish, and the space is a bit small. If I change cars in the future, I'd like to switch to an SUV.
Gao Zhiyuan: SUVs are great, with good visibility and strong off-road capability. Do you have any preferred brands in mind? German? Japanese? Or do you prefer to support domestic brands?

Yin Hao: Personally, I still lean toward Japanese cars, especially Toyota. They feel sturdy, durable, fuel-efficient, and relatively cheap to maintain, which suits a practical person like me. Models like the RAV4 or Wildlander are pretty good. German cars have great technology, but I feel the maintenance costs in the long run are a bit higher. Domestic cars have made significant progress, but I might need to wait a few more years before considering them.
Gao Zhiyuan: That makes sense, Toyota is indeed reliable. However, it ultimately depends on your budget and needs at that time. When you're ready to change, I'll help you take a good look.

Chen Jie: Haozi, regarding your question about half-marathon supplies: take one energy gel at the 10-kilometer mark and another at the 15-kilometer mark. Don’t take them too early. As for water, drink a small amount every 2.5 kilometers—don’t wait until you’re thirsty to gulp it down. The ankle issue is a bit more complicated. The way I recommended using the fascia ball involves specific techniques for pressure and frequency, so follow my instructions and don’t improvise. I’ve sent you the details on WeChat. Please take a look.
Zhang Jianguo: Haozi, have you been in touch with Xiao Zhou lately? He seems a bit off recently.
Yin Hao: He said a few words in the group chat last week, and it seemed like he didn't have much to say. What's up, Lao Zhang?
Zhang Jianguo: He called me and said that the project in Shenzhen is tight, with overtime work every day, and the pressure is too high.
Zhang Jianguo: Because of this, he had several arguments with his girlfriend and just broke up with her the other day. Sigh, it sounds quite depressing.
Yin Hao: No wonder. I was wondering why he hasn't been online for games. I'll give him a call later to chat.
Wang Lei: Haozi, my playlist is running dry lately. Any new song recommendations?
Yin Hao: I've been listening to some Chinese-style electronic music lately, and it's really addictive.
Wang Lei: Chinese-style electronic music? What's it like?

Yin Hao: It's like mixing traditional instruments such as the guzheng and flute with the rhythm and arrangement of modern electronic music. The combination feels incredibly cool while still retaining its charm.

Yin Hao: There are a few with a strong sense of rhythm that I listen to during my morning runs, and my pace easily syncs up. There are also some with more soothing melodies that I listen to after work when I get home, which feels very stress-relieving.
Wang Lei: Sounds good, send me a few playlist links to try.
Wang Lei: Haozi, are you off work yet? Want to play some games together tonight?
Yin Hao: Just got home, feeling a bit tired today, want to rest for a while and listen to some music.
Wang Lei: What are you listening to? Any good songs to recommend lately?
Yin Hao: Recently, I've been listening to an independent musician called 'Mountain Echoes.' The style is quite fresh, a bit like folk music with a touch of electronic elements.

Yin Hao: He has a song called "Morning Light" that I particularly love. The lyrics describe the feeling of seeing the city slowly wake up while running early in the morning, which really resonates with me.
Zhang Jianguo (Comrade-in-arms): Brothers, have you watched the documentary "Craftsmanship Forges Dreams" that was recently broadcast on CCTV? It's about mechanical manufacturing.
Zhou Xiaofeng (Comrade-in-arms): I took a quick glance, and it's quite in-depth from a technical perspective. Those five-axis machining centers are truly impressive.
Yin Hao: I've seen it. The technical demonstration was indeed impressive, but what moved me the most wasn't the machine itself.

Yin Hao: It's the veteran craftsmen inside, who have spent their entire lives as fitters, welders, and assemblers. Their skills are almost magical, and they can judge errors based on experience and intuition. That kind of human craftsmanship and legacy carries more warmth than cold, impersonal machines.
Zhang Jianguo (Comrade-in-arms): Haha, Haozi, you're really resonating with this, thinking about your master, aren't you?
Wu Zhiqiang: Yin Hao, tomorrow morning at the usual spot, we'll continue last week's unfinished discussion about new energy vehicles while fishing.
I just planned a trip to Songjiang Library during the lunch break to focus on checking the content of the Shanghai Electrician Certificate exam syllabus. Do you have any related suggestions?
summarized_info: Yin Hao sent a text message to his colleague, mentioning that during the lunch break, he planned to go to the Songjiang Library to look up information on the Shanghai Electrician Certificate exam syllabus.

message_content: Chen Jie: The atmosphere during this morning's run was fantastic, and the technical insights you shared along the way were truly inspiring, especially the part about program optimization.
Zhao Lei: Haozi, how have you been lately? I’ve got some new changes on my end—let’s chat about it.
Yin Hao: Not bad, same as usual. What's the change? Got a promotion and a raise?

Zhao Lei: It's not a promotion, but an internal transfer. Our company has always been engaged in traditional e-commerce, but this year the boss wants to venture into cross-border live-streaming sales and has established a new department.
Yin Hao: Live streaming? That's quite different from the operations work you used to do.

Zhao Lei: Yeah, it's quite a challenge. But I think it's an opportunity, so I applied. Now I've been transferred to work on live streaming operations and planning, learning everything from scratch. It feels a bit more interesting than staring at data reports all day.
Gao Zhiyuan: Haozi, are you free this weekend? There's a new sci-fi movie out, and I heard the special effects are mind-blowing. Want to go see it together?
Yin Hao: Sci-fi movies are fine, as long as they're not the kind that drag on with romance. Last time I watched a romantic art film with someone, I almost fell asleep.
Gao Zhiyuan: Haha, I knew you wouldn't like that kind of movie. How about a suspense film? There's a domestic mystery one that's been getting high ratings lately.

Yin Hao: Suspense is okay; it's interesting to use your brain and guess who the killer is. I can also watch war movies—after all, as a man, I have some sentiment for guns and artillery. But those slow-paced ones that only focus on emotional entanglements—I really can't get into them. It feels like a waste of time.
Master Sun: Xiao Yin, I saw you operating that new program very steadily today, much better than my nephew.
Yin Hao: You flatter me, Master Sun. What's wrong with your nephew?

Master Sun: Sigh, my sister's son just graduated this year, majoring in mechanical design. He's quite honest, but too introverted and not good at talking. He's had several job interviews recently, but none of them worked out. He came back feeling really down.
Yin Hao: Indeed, communication plays a significant role in interviews. How about letting him start by gaining some experience in a smaller company first?
Master Sun: That's exactly what I advised him to do—keep working and build a solid foundation of skills first. It's just that seeing him so disheartened is a bit heartbreaking.
Angkor: Xiao Yin, are you going to Dianshan Lake this weekend? I heard there are big crucian carp recently.
Yin Hao: Let's go, Wuge. I've been thinking about upgrading my gear anyway. I feel like my current set is a bit outdated.
Angkor: What do you want to change? The rod or the reel?

Yin Hao: Neither. I've got my eye on an electronic fishing float, the kind with night vision, temperature display, and bite alarm. My old float is too hard to see at night, and the signals are unclear.

Angkor: That is indeed convenient, especially for night fishing. My friend is using one and says that with the sensitivity properly adjusted, it clearly distinguishes between small fish nibbling and big fish biting. Which brand are you planning to buy?
Yin Hao, we had a good chat just now. Regarding that plan, let's set it for next Wednesday at 7 PM.
Chen Xiaowen: Haohao, have you been busy with work lately? I've got something on my mind and wanted to talk to you about it.
Yin Hao: Wenwen, I'm doing okay, just got off work. What's up? Are things not going well at work?

Chen Xiaowen: Well, there's a new UI design supervisor in our department, a woman, and she's particularly assertive. During meetings, no matter what proposal I put forward, she can always find a bunch of faults and dismiss me in front of the whole team, which makes me feel really embarrassed and quite stifled.
Yin Hao: That's too much? Isn't she deliberately targeting you? Did you have any issues with her before?

Chen Xiaowen: Not at all, it's been like this since she arrived. It feels like she's trying to establish authority by making an example of me, a long-time employee. It's really tough; going to work every day feels like a punishment.

Gao Zhiyuan: Haozi, are you free this weekend? There's a new sci-fi blockbuster called "The Temporal Rift" that just came out. I heard the special effects are mind-blowing. Want to go watch it together?

Yin Hao: Lao Gao, I generally watch sci-fi movies. But it depends on the genre. I don’t really like those convoluted time travel films—they tend to confuse me, and there are often a lot of plot holes.

Gao Zhiyuan: Haha, are you referring to the kind of stuff like the grandfather paradox and parallel universes that are hard to untangle? It’s indeed mind-bending. So, which type do you prefer? The kind like "Independence Day" where they fight aliens, or the kind like "I, Robot" where AI rebels?

Yin Hao: I find movies about fighting aliens or addressing future societal issues, like resource competition and class division, to be more realistic. AI-themed films are fine too, but they shouldn't be too far-fetched. What I can't stand the most are those with messy timelines that can't be properly resolved in the end—they just give me a headache.
Gao Zhiyuan: Got it, you're a logic enthusiast who hates bugs. Let me check the reviews to see if this movie is the kind that goes in circles. If not, I'll invite you again.
Sun Jianguo: Xiao Yin, Wang Lei, this kid, is about to have a happy event recently.
Yin Hao: Huh? Master Sun, what's the good news? Did he get a promotion?
Sun Jianguo: It's not about work. He went back to his hometown in Henan last month, and his family arranged a blind date for him, which turned out successful.
Yin Hao: Really? This guy has been keeping it under wraps, didn't even mention it in the group chat.

Sun Jianguo: He also quietly told me during lunch today that the girl is nice and her family is satisfied, and they plan to get married by the end of the year. He asked us not to spread the word for now, as he hasn't figured out how to tell you guys yet.
Gao Zhiyuan: Haozi, are you going to KTV this weekend? There are a few new upbeat songs out recently, let's go belt them out.

Yin Hao: Lao Gao, let's skip this week. I'm not sure if it's because I've been running a bit too much during training lately, but after work, I just want to stay at home quietly and listen to some soothing music.
Gao Zhiyuan: Oh, have you changed your taste? Didn't you used to prefer energetic music? What are you listening to now?

Yin Hao: Just some pure music, or very light music. My phone app recommended a "Sleep Aid and Stress Relief" playlist, and it sounds quite comfortable, able to relax the mind. It feels more satisfying than noisy and chaotic music.
Gao Zhiyuan: Got it, you've entered health maintenance mode. Alright, let's plan something once you're back in form.
Zhang Wei: Haozi, are you busy? I need to tell you something—Qiangzi's situation has changed.
Yin Hao: Just got off work, what's the change? Did he quit his e-commerce operations job in Hangzhou?
Zhang Wei: Yes, he resigned. He said the e-commerce industry is too competitive, with overtime work every day, and his health couldn't take it anymore. He plans to return to Nantong.
Yin Hao: Going back to your hometown is good too, less pressure. What are his plans after returning?

Zhang Wei: From what he said, he wants to partner with a friend who runs a repair shop in Rudong and start his own auto repair business. After all, he has always been good with his hands, and this would be a return to his old profession.
Wang Lei: Yin Hao, wanna team up for some gaming tonight? Let's climb the ranks in the new season!
Yin Hao: Not playing tonight, I'm catching up on a TV series. The third season of "Like a Flowing River" just updated, I have to watch it.
Wang Lei: Oh, you watch this kind of serious drama? What's it about?

Yin Hao: It's about factories and technology after the reform and opening-up. The character Song Yunhui in the show started out as a technician and worked his way up to become a factory director. I really admire how he stuck to his technical standards no matter what challenges he faced. It feels a bit like what we do in machining—precision is everything, and even the slightest deviation isn't acceptable.
Wang Lei: Got it, the resonance among tech people. Alright, you go ahead and take a look, let's meet up again tomorrow.
Yin Tao: Haozi, what have you been up to lately? I just had a call with Sister Wenwen.
Yin Hao: Just got off work and I'm cooking. What's up, Wenwen? You sound like something's on your mind.

Yin Tao: Sigh, her company recently underwent some structural adjustments, which completely dismantled their entire UI design department. All the staff were scattered and reassigned to various product lines.
Yin Hao: Huh? Then which group was Wenwen assigned to? Hasn't she always been working in the e-commerce sector?

Yin Tao: I was assigned to a new project group that develops enterprise service software, and I am completely unfamiliar with the business. The key issue is that the new leader is particularly pushy, constantly monitoring progress every day. She is under immense pressure and vented to me, saying she is almost depressed.
Wu Zhiqiang: Xiao Yin, the weather is nice this weekend. How about going to Dianshan Lake to cast a few lines? I found a new fishing spot.
Yin Hao: Brother Wu, I might not be available this weekend as I have to work overtime to finish an urgent task. Lately, I only have some free time in the evenings.
Wu Zhiqiang: Understood, work comes first. So what do you do in the evenings? Still playing your Honor of Kings?

Yin Hao: I've been playing fewer video games lately. Recently, I discovered a new pleasure: preparing a couple of small dishes in the evening, pouring a glass of yellow wine, connecting my phone to a Bluetooth speaker, and playing some folk songs or light music, like those by Zhao Lei or Li Jian. It’s incredibly relaxing—a completely different world from the roaring machines in the workshop during the day.
Wu Zhiqiang: Haha, you really know how to enjoy life. This kind of vibe is nice, healthier than playing video games. Alright, let's plan for next week then.
Zhang Jianguo: Haozi, what have you been up to lately? I've run into something really bizarre over here—it's both infuriating and amusing.
Yin Hao: What's up, Lao Zhang? Tell me about it. I just got off work and I'm having dinner right now.
Zhang Jianguo: There's a new member at our gym who, somehow, found out that I used to be in the military. He's been pestering me to teach him what he calls "military combat techniques."
Yin Hao: Haha, isn't that a good thing? Taking on an apprentice.

Zhang Jianguo: Good, my foot! I made it clear that I'm just a fitness trainer and can't teach combat. But this guy's gone crazy. Now he comes to the gym every day with a notebook, waiting for me, saying he wants to record my "training routine" and study my "combat skills." I'm almost at my wit's end with him—there's no way to avoid him.
Gao Zhiyuan: Haozi, is the KTV playlist updated for the weekend? Don't let it be all those outdated pop songs again.
Yin Hao: Old Gao, you just don't get it. My taste in music has changed a bit lately, and I've discovered some new stuff.
Gao Zhiyuan: Oh? Let's hear it, it's not that you've started listening to symphonies, is it?

Yin Hao: Not exactly. It's Chinese-style instrumental music, but not the old-fashioned kind. It blends traditional instruments like the erhu and guzheng with electronic drums and synthesizers, creating a really captivating sound—both flavorful and engaging. I listen to it while repairing small appliances or simply relaxing, and it feels great.
Gao Zhiyuan: Not bad, Haozi, your taste is improving. But KTV doesn't have these songs. You'll still need to prepare something you can belt out over the weekend!
Wang Lei: Haozi, wanna play ranked games tonight? Let's climb the ladder in the new season.
Yin Hao: Not tonight, I need to have a video chat with my brother. He's been dealing with some troubles lately.
Wang Lei: What's wrong? Isn't your brother doing quite well selling cars in Suzhou?

Yin Hao: Yeah, but their company recently underwent a restructuring, merging his entire sales department. Now the company is asking him to either transfer to the marketing department or take compensation and leave.
Wang Lei: Has he made up his mind? The marketing department is quite different from sales, isn't it?

Yin Hao: He's in a dilemma. He's not familiar with the marketing department, and he's heard that the pressure there is quite high. He found out that a new high-end brand 4S store in the industrial park is recruiting a sales manager, with good benefits, but he would have to start from scratch to build a customer base.
Angkor: Xiao Yin, how about going to Dianshan Lake this weekend? I heard the crucian carp are biting well lately.

Yin Hao: Great, Brother Wu! I was just thinking of trying out the new bait I bought. By the way, I checked out the fishing rod you recommended last time—it's too stiff, and I don't think I'll get used to it.

Angkor: Haha, that H-tuned one is specifically designed for those who play in black pits and compete for fast fish. You usually do more wild fishing, and occasionally join me in a black pit, so there's no need to be that extreme.

Yin Hao: Yeah, I still think the medium-hard action (M-action) all-around rod suits me best. When fishing in the wild, it can handle carp weighing three to five pounds, and it also feels decent when fishing for crucian carp in stocked ponds—it's quite versatile. Although softer rods (like L-action stream rods) offer a better feel, they make me nervous when encountering larger fish.
Angkor: That makes sense. What suits you best is indeed the best. The M-tone is truly versatile and a mainstay for wild fishing. See you this weekend, and bring your 'versatile tool' along.
Yin Hao, I heard you mention getting the flu vaccine at noon. Is the arm soreness really that mild for just one day? I'm thinking of getting vaccinated too.
Liu Zhiqiang: Haozi, are you off work? Squad Leader Wang seemed a bit down today and didn't say much during lunch.
Yin Hao: Just changed clothes. It is a bit strange; he's usually the most active. Do you know what's going on?

Liu Zhiqiang: We chatted a bit while smoking just now. His landlord suddenly said they're selling the house and gave him a month to move out. He's really worried about finding a place now, especially since rents in Minhang have been skyrocketing.
Yin Hao: Huh? So sudden. No wonder he's in no mood. I'll ask him later to see if I can help. My landlady, Sister Li, has a wide network and might have some connections.
Zhang Wei: Brother Hao, how's the house hunting in Shanghai going? Which area have you set your sights on?
Yin Hao: Still looking, considering areas around Songjiang, Qingpu, and Jiading. The total price can't be too high, but I need to be selective about the environment.
Zhang Wei: Environment? What kind are you looking for? Close to the mall, convenient for eating, drinking, and having fun?

Yin Hao: That's not the primary concern. I actually prefer having a park nearby, or being close to places like Dianshan Lake or Sheshan Mountain. That way, I can have a good route for my morning runs, and on weekends, if I feel like fishing, it's convenient without having to drive too far. It's peaceful and good for my health.
Zhang Wei: Got it, you're integrating your hobby into your life! Looks like next time I visit you in Shanghai, we'll be meeting by the lake.
Zhang Jianguo: Haozi, what are you up to? I just finished a video call with Xiao Zhou. That guy has had two happy events recently!
Yin Hao: Old Zhang! Just got back from a run. What's up with Xiao Zhou? Another breakthrough at work in Shenzhen?

Zhang Jianguo: More than just work! Didn't he keep saying last year that he wanted to settle down? He finally did it—bought a small two-bedroom apartment in Longhua, Shenzhen. Although it's a bit remote, at least it's his own home.
Yin Hao: That's great! With housing prices in Shenzhen being so high, he's moving really fast. That must be quite a lot of pressure, right?

Zhang Jianguo: There's definitely pressure, but good things come in pairs for him. He's settled on a house and is planning to get engaged to his girlfriend of two years. He says they'll hold the wedding once the house is renovated. Looks like our "iron triangle" needs to start preparing the wedding gift money, huh? Haha.
Wang Lei: Haozi, are you going to the car exhibition this weekend? I heard there are quite a few new SUV models.

Yin Hao: Thanks, monitor. I need to review the materials for the technician exam this weekend. Besides, buying a car is still a long way off for me; I'll think about it once I have some progress with the house.
Wang Lei: That's true, let's settle the housing first. But you can start thinking about what kind of car you like, so you'll have a clear goal in mind.
Yin Hao: To be honest, my thoughts might differ from many others. I'm not particularly drawn to flashy large screens or autonomous driving features.

Yin Hao: For me, safety is the top priority, especially features like automatic emergency braking and airbags—they must be fully equipped. Next, maintenance and repairs should be convenient and affordable, with easily accessible parts. After all, as someone in the technical field, I understand that a car is meant to be used, not worshipped. What matters most is durability, reliability, and peace of mind. Take my dad’s old Jetta, for example—it ran for over a decade, and repair shops were everywhere, so we never had to worry.
Zhang Jianguo: Haozi, how have you been lately? I've encountered something really bizarre here—it's both infuriating and amusing.
Yin Hao: Old Zhang, what's up? Let's hear it.
Zhang Jianguo: We have a new auntie member at our gym, almost sixty years old, and she insists on losing weight. That's pretty normal, right?

Zhang Jianguo: As it turns out, she somehow heard that I used to be a soldier. Now she pesters me every day, insisting that I teach her "military boxing," claiming it's effective for weight loss and has a powerful presence. I explained for a long time that it's meant for training and isn't suitable for her, but she still doesn't believe me and says I'm keeping it to myself.
Yin Hao: Hahaha! This auntie is quite something. So what did you do?

Zhang Jianguo: What else can we do? Just patiently persuade her and design suitable aerobic and flexibility training for the elderly. It's just that I find it both amusing and frustrating—using military-style boxing for weight loss, that's quite an unusual way of thinking.
Gao Zhiyuan: Haozi, wanna play ranked games tonight? Gotta climb the ladder in the new season.
Yin Hao: Later, I just got off work and want to listen to some music to relax first.
Gao Zhiyuan: Listening to your pop songs again? Any good songs to recommend lately?
Yin Hao: My taste has changed a bit recently. I still listen to energetic music while running, but I prefer pure music or light music when I get home.

Yin Hao: For example, piano music, natural white noise, and things like that, they seem to calm the mind, making it particularly relaxing. Sometimes, it also helps with focusing better when reading or learning.
Gao Zhiyuan: You're really into health preservation now? Alright, go ahead and focus on that. Just call me online at nine o'clock.
Li Qiang: Haozi, have you seen the new movie "The Artisan" recently? It's about a master CNC operator mentoring his apprentice. The online reviews seem to be pretty good.
Yin Hao: Yes, I watched it last week with my colleague Wang Lei. It left a deep impression on me.
Li Qiang: Oh? How so? Do you think it's too idealistic? Our industry isn't as glamorous as it appears in movies.

Yin Hao: On the contrary. I think it captures the essence of our profession. It’s not about glamour, but the grounded feeling of making a living with craftsmanship and striving for perfection in our work. In the film, the master craftsman says that the precision on the blueprint is achieved through the hands and the heart, not printed by a diploma.

Yin Hao: It made me realize that even as vocational school graduates working in the workshop, as long as our skills are solid, we can earn respect and create value just as much as office workers. That's what moved me the most.

Wu Zhiqiang: Xiao Yin, spring has arrived, and the fishing conditions at Dianshan Lake are starting to pick up. Last time you mentioned wanting to add a new fishing rod to your collection—have you found one you like? Nowadays, ultra-light carbon rods or smart rods are quite popular.

Yin Hao: Brother Wu, I've looked into it. Those fancy smart fishing rods seem flashy but impractical to me, and they break easily. Ultra-light carbon rods are good, but they're too delicate. I'm afraid I'm a bit heavy-handed, and with the rough conditions of wild fishing, I'd be heartbroken if they got bumped or scratched.
Wu Zhiqiang: Haha, so you're still sticking to the old ways. Looking for something durable?

Yin Hao: Yes. I prefer medium to long sections of fiberglass or composite rods. They might be a bit heavier, but they have strong backbone and are durable. Whether it's casting with a big swing or encountering larger fish, I feel confident. The price is also reasonable, and I don't feel bad if they get damaged—tools, after all, reliability comes first.
Wu Zhiqiang: That makes sense, just like you—down-to-earth. I have two of these rods in stock at my shop, great value for money. Want to come check them out this weekend?
Xiao Yin, the repair shop will open as usual tomorrow morning. If you want to come and observe, you can just come directly. All the tools are available here at Jianguo Repair Shop.
Jie: Hao, thanks for treating us to the post-run meal today. The food at Fulin Kitchen was really great! Next time we go for a run or train together, it's my treat.

Haozi, what a surprise to see you in the group! We haven’t seen each other since elementary school, right? I never expected we’d both be in Shanghai. How about catching up over a meal sometime? This is Li Feng.

Mom, it's getting colder here in Shanghai, so it must be cooling down in Nantong too. I bought self-heating knee pads for Dad since his joints are sensitive to the cold. I also got thick vests for both of you. I added a note to the order saying, "It's getting cold, so please stay warm." I've already shared it in the group chat.
Mom, tomorrow evening Dad and I will do the final testing of those safety devices at home, and I’ll explain how to use them to you in person again. Please wait for us at home.

Dad, the official appointment letter came through today. Starting next month, I'll be in the senior technician position. The responsibilities are heavier, but the salary increase has finally been approved—another step closer to the goal.

Old Chen: Haozi, you mustn't rush things with an ankle injury. Last time I had a similar situation, I rested completely for a week, applying ice and stretching every day, and only dared to jog again when it was completely free of swelling and pain. Don't even think about running this week—focus on observation for now.
Yang Zai, it's been such a long time! I'm Yin Hao, your elementary school classmate. I saw you in our hometown group chat, and I'm so excited!
Just finished, getting ready to head back. I'm exhausted today.
Yin Hao: Just finished the plan, printed a copy and posted it on the wall. This year, I'm aiming to become a senior technician, and the tasks are scheduled all the way to the fourth quarter.

Team Leader Zhang, the first trial cutting of the high-precision special-shaped part has been completed. The dimensional inspection is qualified, with tolerances controlled within 0.01mm. Batch processing is currently underway, and the machine tool is operating smoothly.

I heard that Aunt Chen is hospitalized. How is she doing? I'm really worried. It must be too exhausting for you to take care of her all by yourself. I'm available during lunch breaks or after work in the next few days, so I can go to the hospital to help look after her for a while, allowing you to take a break. Please don’t hesitate to ask.

Xiao Liu: Did you get the lease renewal sorted? You seemed in a hurry yesterday.  
Yin Hao: Yeah, just finished signing with the landlord at a café. The conversation went smoothly. Mainly, I find the location convenient for both the office and the training ground, and I get along well with the neighbors, so I decided to stay.

Yin Hao: Chen Jie, regarding the terms for our shared living arrangement, I've drafted a simple outline covering public hygiene duties, expense sharing, and quiet hours. Would you be available to go through it point by point tonight when it's convenient for you?
See you at the usual place this afternoon, and make sure to bring everything.
See you at the usual spot this afternoon, and make sure to bring everything.
To Li Si: Just got off work, finally finished today's urgent tasks.

Me: ['Precision Engineering Technical Discussion Group'] The preliminary investigation of the morning's aperture fluctuation issue has been completed. Master Sun and Wang Lei have conducted inspections on the spindle and cutting tools respectively, with no abnormalities found. The data has been compiled. The next focus should shift to the program dimension. Engineer Liu, when convenient, could we meet to discuss the possibility of optimizing the program parameters?
Yin Hao: Happy Army Day! While jogging this morning, I recalled our morning drills in the military. The discipline we developed back then still benefits me today. Let's stay in touch!
Master: See you this afternoon, remember to bring the materials. I'll be waiting for you in the lounge area.
[Zhihu] The answer you bookmarked, "A Guide to Avoiding Pitfalls in Car Maintenance for Beginners," has been updated by the author.

Squad Leader Wang, the processing and inspection tasks for the special-shaped part you assigned have been completed. The quality inspection report has just been received, and the results are qualified.

Master Chen, this is Yin Hao. I will arrive punctually at your repair shop located at No. 1, Lane 2369, Rongle East Road at 9 a.m. tomorrow, Saturday, for observation and learning. Thank you for your trouble.

Yin Hao: Master Sun, thank you for your advice on preparing for the senior technician certificate during lunch. Your experience sharing was very helpful to me, and I will incorporate it into my plans.

Master Sun, regarding the vibration issue you mentioned this morning, I read that Zhihu article and found it quite enlightening. I will refer to the ideas from it when discussing the coolant solution with Engineer Liu this afternoon.

Zhiqiang, regarding the program optimization plan we discussed this afternoon, I have confirmed it. We will first adjust the feed rate for the precision machining of the hole positions from F180 to F150 to observe whether there is any improvement in the stability of the hole diameter dimensions and surface quality. We will conduct a trial machining verification during the early shift tomorrow.
Yin Hao: The morning processing tasks have been completed, and all spot checks have passed. Everything has been carried out as planned, and we can continue in the afternoon.

Master, today's meeting has concluded. The team leader accepted my suggestion regarding cutting temperature and assigned me to be responsible for data tracking. I felt a bit nervous while speaking during the meeting, but thanks to your usual guidance on paying attention to data details.

Liu Zhiqiang: Hao Ge, the optimized program has been imported into that vertical machining center. We're waiting for you to come and start it up. Master Sun and I are waiting for you by the machine tool. Let's run it first with the parameters we discussed yesterday and test the results.

Engineer Liu, regarding the technical issue with Machine No. 5, we will implement the optimization according to the plan discussed yesterday this afternoon. Have you completed the adjustments to your program?
Wang Lei, the supervisor just called to remind us to pay attention to data accuracy during the morning meeting. I have already updated the PPT.
Are you free tonight? I'd like to invite you to dinner.
Yin Hao: This afternoon's training goal was successfully completed! Feeling great, getting closer to the half marathon. How has your exercise been lately?
Yin Hao: The training goal for this afternoon has been successfully completed! Feeling great, getting closer to the half marathon. How has your exercise been lately?
Zhiqiang: Brother Hao, it was a great gathering today, the dried clams were so fresh! How about fishing at the usual spot next week?
Zhiqiang: Brother Hao, I had a great time hanging out today. The dried clams were so fresh! How about fishing at our usual spot next week?

Yin Hao, Auntie says the hospital food is too bland and tasteless, so she hasn't eaten much these past two days. Her son is busy with work, and I've been constantly worried, fearing she might not get enough nutrition, which could affect her wound healing.
Coach Wang: For tomorrow's long-distance training run, try using energy gels as planned, and make sure to record your physical reactions.

Yin Hao, look at the water level changes, you need to adjust your bait. Reduce some of the fishy bait, add the gluten powder cautiously, and highlighting the natural grain flavor is the key. Brother Wu.

Yin Hao: Brother Jie, I've sent you the screenshot of today's 10K data! My first 10 kilometers, and it felt really great. After stretching and taking a quick shower, I had a cup of yogurt and felt revived. I'm thinking of trying LSD (Long Slow Distance) next week to build a foundation for the half marathon. Are you free to join me? Oh, by the way, I just washed my running clothes and checked the fridge—there are still enough ingredients.
Yin Hao, I've sent you some Huangshan specialties - baked cakes and Maofeng tea. Give them a try. Please keep an eye out for the delivery.

Master, I have prepared this year's career development plan as you suggested last time and printed a copy. The main focus is on obtaining the senior technician certification. I'm not sure if the roadmap is properly laid out, so I would appreciate it if you could review it and provide some advice.
summarized_info: I sent a text message to my mentor, Sun Jianguo, showing him my newly formulated annual career development plan and seeking his advice.

message_content: Hao Hao, drive slowly on the road. By the way, did you bring all those safety gadgets you mentioned buying for the home last time? When you get home, you can ask your dad to help install them together.

Don't worry, Mom, I've brought everything. One is a motion-sensor night light that automatically turns on when you get up at night, and the other is a non-slip mat to place on the bathroom floor. We can figure out the rest once we get there.

【Department Work Group】@Everyone Due to an unexpected issue with upstream raw materials, the G76 batch components originally scheduled for delivery tomorrow morning require urgent rework and adjustments tonight. Please have the relevant production line day shift staff stay after their shift to assist the process and quality inspection departments in completing the task. The estimated time required is 2-3 hours. Please reply upon receiving this message.

Mr. Wang (Landlord): Xiao Yin, do you understand what we discussed on the phone today? Please clear out the apartment and return the keys by the end of July. We'll handle the deposit settlement at that time. Let's stay in touch.
Yin Hao: Jie, I've sent you today's 10K screenshot! First time completing it, feels amazing! Are you free next week? Let's do a long run together to prepare for the half marathon?

Me: I'm in good form for running today! By the way, I mentioned at noon that I won a small prize and was quite happy. The milk tea I treated you to this afternoon is on me, haha.
Chen Jie: Thanks, bro! Keep up the good work in the next training session!

【Fishing Gear World】Dear member, the items from your order (ending in 7782) have been shipped: 1. Competition bait set, 2. Nano float set, 3. Fishing foam roller. The tracking number is SF1234567890. Please keep an eye out for delivery.
I just renewed my lease, and my neighbor Aunt Chen is really kind—she often looks out for me, which makes me feel very warm.

(To Li Xiuying) Sister Li, I just thought about it, and your timeline for selling the house is tight. On my end, the final move-out date can be set for July 31st. Additionally, regarding the compensation and future house viewings, what do you think about the proposal of one month's rent (3,000) as compensation and requiring a half-day advance notice for viewings? Can we sign a supplementary agreement tomorrow to confirm this?

(To Chen Jie) Jie, regarding the conversation we had during our last run about the landlord selling the house. I've been thinking it over these past few days, and the budget I saved for moving is now sufficient. I wanted to formally ask if you'd be interested in renting a two-bedroom apartment together in Songjiang? We can split the rent based on room size or go half and half, and take turns with cleaning duties. If you're up for it, how about we check out some places this weekend and finalize the details?

Master Chen, good evening. I was tidying up at home during the day and found an old floor fan that isn't getting power. After watching your live stream tonight, I was quite inspired. I did a preliminary check and didn't notice any signs of burning or broken wires. Could I ask for a few more troubleshooting ideas from you?

Hao'er, I didn't finish in the video. Now all the new harvesters at the station come with computer boards and remote diagnostics, but when they break down, the screens are full of codes, and us old-timers are completely in the dark.
Yin Hao: Today, the positioning accuracy and repeatability of each axis of the machine tool were verified using a laser interferometer and standard gauge blocks. The data has been saved.

Xiao Yin, the notebooks and exercise sets I gave you during the lunch break are the ones I used when I was preparing for the senior technician exam. They contain many practical cases and highlighted key points. Take your time to review them, and there’s no rush to return them.
Tao, the physical examination report is out, and it shows a bit of fatty liver. I'll have to control my drinking at gatherings from now on, so please keep an eye on me.

Great! Today is Sunday, and the fishing conditions are normal. The environment at that pound pond is quite decent. Wishing you a great catch, and looking forward to seeing your fishing haul when you return.

Yin Hao, I've sent you some Huangshan specialties, including Huangshan sesame cakes and this year's fresh Maofeng tea. They are all authentic local flavors from our area. The comrades shared them, and I saved a portion for you. The package should arrive today, so please keep an eye out for it. Old Zhang.
Master Sun, during the lunch break, I conducted a mental simulation as planned, going through the entire high-intensity process from yesterday. The results were good, and my confidence has increased.

Today's gathering was delightful, and I learned a lot from your experiences in buying houses. I've been adjusting my lifestyle habits lately, so I intentionally chose tea over alcohol today, and it felt really good.
Yin Hao: Ran 10.5 kilometers this morning, feeling good, ready to head to work.
Chen Jie: Are all the equipment ready? I'm all set on my end. I took a short nap during the lunch break. Let's head to the botanical garden now and meet at the entrance.

I've been practicing running lately and feel my old knee pads are a bit loose. Jie, what brand of protective gear did you use when you ran the half marathon before? I'm participating in a competition at the end of the month and want to get a new set, so I'm preparing in advance.
By the way, Master Sun, I have a running race on the weekend of May 25th. I need to take half a day off on Saturday for overtime work, and I'll be participating in the competition in the afternoon.

Teacher Liu, sorry to bother you. I have registered for the CNC Senior Technician exam this year, and I noticed on the application form that the test center is at a university in Songjiang, but the specific name wasn't provided. Do you know which school it is? I'd like to check the route in advance.

Mom, I'll be back for Mid-Autumn Festival. I just got the notice that the senior worker exam is on October 12th, and the test center is at Shanghai University of Engineering Science, right next to the company, which is quite convenient.
Wu Ge, I heard there's a fishing competition at Dianshan Lake during the National Day holiday with a pretty high prize? What's the exact date? I'd like to give it a try.
Bro, I only have one day off on October 4th during the National Day holiday to participate in a fishing competition. I’ll have to work overtime for the next few days to rush an urgent order.
Mom, I've been craving some hometown specialties lately. If you have time, could you send me some local products? Anything would be fine.
Xiaohao, did you receive the clams and seaweed your mom asked me to send? They’re the best from our Rudong—perfect for making a delicious soup.
Weige, the preview says a new skin is coming for the 10th anniversary of Honor of Kings, with a mecha style that looks absolutely awesome. But it doesn’t specify which hero it’s for.
Haozi, log in tonight to claim the anniversary rewards! The new mecha skin for Sun Shangxiang is available for free in the event, and it's said to feel pretty good to use.
Squad Leader Wang, is the end-of-month dinner settled? I heard we're going to have local cuisine.
Mr. Liu, the weekend dinner is at the 'Lao Sheng Xing' on Xinzhuang Highway. It's on your way from Kunshan, so make sure you don't take the wrong route.

Don't even mention it. Recently, the company has been focusing on skill enhancement, and next month, we are required to attend a mandatory two-week CNC programming training. It's giving me a headache.
When does the training start?
The 15th of next month. What about you? Didn't you say you also wanted to take the advanced certification exam? Any updates?
You have training next month, and I have an exam next month. Both of us are going to be busy.
Haha, yes. My training starts on September 15th. When is your exam?
Xiao Yin, are you free this weekend? Let's have a meal together, my treat.
Are you free, Master Sun? What's the good news?
Haha, the certificate is out, so happy!
Master Sun, is your Senior Technician Certificate displayed on the factory's honor wall? I saw it when I passed by today.
Yes, that's the one. The factory insisted on hanging it up, which is quite embarrassing. Prepare well, and you'll be able to get one next year.

Yin Hao, I heard you've been having some neck discomfort lately? There's a new traditional Chinese medicine therapy center that just opened downstairs in our company building. There's a Dr. Zeng there who is particularly skilled in massage techniques. I recommend you give it a try.
Fangfang, regarding Dr. Zeng Wei you mentioned last time, I've made an appointment for Saturday afternoon. What's the specific address on Zhangjiang Road again?
Yes, Dr. Zeng Wei. It's located at Shop 108, in the commercial area of the Zhangjiang Road Technology Park Apartment. You can find it by navigating to 'Kangjiantang'.
Haozi! I had an amazing fishing day in the river back in my hometown! Caught a huge fish that almost snapped my rod!
Sure! How big? What kind of fish?
Didn't bring a scale, but I'd estimate it's over five or six pounds. As for what kind of fish it is, wait for me to post it on my social media for you to guess, haha!
Are you going back to Nantong for May Day? That wild bream we caught last time, my mom braised it, and it tasted absolutely amazing—too bad you weren't there.
Bream is indeed delicious. I'm working overtime during the May Day holiday and can't go back, so eat more on my behalf.
Qiangzi, how have you been lately? Are you planning to buy anything for Double Eleven?
No need to buy a phone this year. The company gave out new phones as quarterly rewards, saving me some money.
How is the camera on your new phone? I've been thinking about getting one with a better camera recently.
The Huawei Mate 70 truly excels in photography, especially in night scenes. You can visit a store to experience its feel in person.
Xiao Hao, we have a little dog at home now, and it's really smart. You'll get to see it when you come back for the New Year.
Really, Uncle? What breed is it? Have you given it a name?
Little stray dog, found it. Let your aunt name it, she's still thinking.
Uncle, have you picked a name for the puppy yet? Send a photo to have a look.
I've named it Yuanbao. Yuanbao is very lively, and I'll send you a photo on WeChat.
Yin Hao, are we still going to Dianshan Lake this weekend? My rod that broke last time can't be fixed, so I want to buy a new one.
After looking around, I still want to buy a Daiwa. It feels more comfortable to use. Shimano is too expensive and a bit over my budget.
Brother Hao, I recently signed up for a half marathon at the end of March to challenge myself. Come cheer me on when the time comes!
Bro, I saw your WeChat moments yesterday. You completed the Songjiang Half Marathon on March 23rd with a great time! Congratulations!
Son, we sent you some freshly harvested clams today, 5 jin (about 2.5 kg), via SF Express. They should arrive tomorrow. You love these the most, don't you?
Have you finished the clams I sent you last time so quickly? I've sent another three jin today for you to enjoy yourself and share with your colleagues and friends.

Haozi, what are your plans for National Day? I'm heading back to my hometown on October 1st, but I'll be passing through Shanghai for some business the week before the holiday. How about we catch up then?
Alright. I'll arrive in Shanghai on September 24th, stay for one night, and leave in the afternoon on the 25th. Let me treat you to hot pot in the evening!
Brother Hao, have you tried the new jungle hero named 'Soul Weaver' in the new season? The skill mechanics are quite interesting, and it seems to suit your playstyle.
I played two rounds last night and felt that the new hero 'Yun Zhong Jun' is indeed viable, but the skill ceiling is a bit high, so I need to practice more.

Xiao Yin, last month I acquired an old Philips stereo system. The previous owner said it wasn't producing any sound. After opening it up, I found that the amplifier module was burnt out. I replaced the part, and now it works perfectly. The sound quality is actually quite good.
Xiao Yin, Aunt Chen from across the hall told me today that her old Philips sound system was fixed by that technician Chen you know. She was really happy and asked me to thank you for the referral.

Xiao Hao, I finally didn't come back empty-handed from my night fishing the other day—I caught a big one! The fight was incredible, probably around seven or eight jin! Just waiting for you to come back during the National Day holiday so I can show off my braised fish skills.

The fish I mentioned the other day, I took it back and measured it later—it's almost eight pounds of yellow catfish, caught from a local wild pond, which is quite rare. When you come back, would you like it braised in soy sauce or cooked as a sour fish soup?
Wang Lei, regarding the buffet voucher from the last company team-building event, it was said to have an expiration date. Do you remember when it becomes valid? I can't find it.

Regarding the meal vouchers from last time, I checked and their validity period starts from the week after the team-building event, which is November 23rd, and lasts until the end of next month. The three of us (you, Yin Hao, and I) can plan to use them together.

Lao Yin, recently our company held an internal competition, and we encountered an incredibly strong newcomer. His physical fitness and skills are both excellent, and he completely overwhelmed a few of our veteran teammates.

Regarding the new employee we talked about last time, I've found out more details. He's a programming expert who just joined the company and was previously a member of his university's basketball team. This is definitely going to boost our company's basketball team's strength.

Hao Hao, my husband works at a company that manufactures precision instruments. Recently, he has been reading a translated book called *The Art of Lean Manufacturing*, which he says is helpful for understanding the technology. He mentioned that there are two translations, and the version translated by Wang Ming and **Chen Feng** is the better one.

Yin Hao, if you want to enhance your theoretical knowledge, you can take a look at *The Art of Lean Manufacturing*. I recommend reading the version translated by Li Hua, as it is more aligned with the actual practices of the domestic industry. The version translated by Wang Ming leans more toward academia, and **Chen Feng**'s translation is also good, but there are some differences in the handling of terminology.
Xiao Yin, please remember to transfer the rent for this quarter in the next couple of days. It's still the same old account. Thank you!
Sister Li, I just checked my mobile banking and it shows that a rent payment of 5500 was transferred to you at 9:30 this morning (the 22nd). Have you received it on your end?

Hao Hao, a relative from your aunt's family hasn't been feeling well lately and wants to go to a major hospital in Shanghai for a check-up. It will likely be around mid to late August, and we may need to trouble you to help with connections or show them the way. The specific illness hasn't been discussed in detail yet.

Did your dad tell you? That relative has some issues with the liver and might need a minor surgery. Your aunt-in-law inquired a bit and said the **surgery** department at Huashan Hospital is quite well-known. When the time comes, see if you can help book an appointment with a specialist.

Wu: Haozi, you here? Just park the car in the back.  
Yin Hao: Yeah, I just got here a moment ago. Saw a guy at the entrance whose car broke down.  
Wu: Battery dead? I’m a bit busy right now. Do you have jumper cables with you?  
Yin Hao: Yeah, I have them in my car. I’ll go see if I can help.  
Wu: Alright, go ahead.  
(One hour later)  
Yin Hao: Wu, just helped that guy get his car started. It was nothing. He said he owes you a meal.  
Wu: He owes you. Nice work, Haozi. You handled it quickly and followed the right steps.  
Yin Hao: Haha, just doing what I should. I’ll hang out in your shop for a bit.

Me: Mom, the company had a fire drill today. I was pretty quick, and my colleagues even praised me. The habits developed in the military are useful at work too. I won't be home for dinner tonight; I'm catching up with some old comrades.
Mom, I've switched to a new phone plan that comes with 500 minutes of talk time, so we can chat more often from now on.
【Industrial and Commercial Bank of China】Your savings card ending with 8899 received a salary deposit of RMB 8,500.00 on August 06. The current balance is RMB 12,345.67.
Yin Hao, congratulations on your promotion! Your new responsibilities have been confirmed and will involve project review-related work. Specific details will be communicated later.

【Landlord Mr. Wang】Xiao Yin, just a heads-up that starting next month, your rent will be adjusted to 3,200 yuan per month. Please take note, and we'll sign a supplementary agreement at the end of the month.
Zhigang, the local specialties have been arranged for shipment and are expected to arrive in your hometown tomorrow. Please keep an eye out for them.

Liu Zhiqiang: Brother Hao, thank you for your concern and advice during lunch. I will arrange to get the flu vaccine as soon as possible. The daily cross-city commute is indeed a concern for my health.

Master, the morning safety inspection has been completed. Following the new procedures from yesterday's training, we focused on checking the sensitivity of the emergency stop buttons and the surrounding environment of the machines, and also cleaned the operation area. All inspection results are qualified, and the protective door interlock is functioning properly.

Lao Zhang, during the lunch break, I wasn't idle—I went on the CNC forum and replied to that post about the common tool setting misconception we often discuss. I wrote it in quite a bit of detail, so it might help some newcomers. Take a look and see if there's anything you'd like to add.

Yin Hao: Brother Jie, the plan you mentioned this morning about 'running a half marathon in the next two years' has really motivated me! Your later advice on adjusting running volume and increasing core training came just in time—I’m planning to implement it right away.
Yin Hao: Chen Jie, this is Yin Hao. Are you free after lunch? I'd like to discuss some ideas about renting a place with you. I think sharing an apartment might be a good option.
Team Leader Wang Lei: Yin Hao, have you received the OA notification? The safety training tomorrow starts at 8:30 in the training room. Don't be late. Please reply upon receipt.

Liu Zhiqiang: Yin Hao, have you seen the grouping? We're in the same group for the practical operation tomorrow afternoon. It seems the list was randomly arranged within the department, and we happened to be paired together.

Zhang Fei: Haozi, our conversation tonight has given me a lot to think about. As designers, when we look at a product, we shouldn’t just focus on the interface—we need to pay attention to the underlying interactions and numerical logic as well. The recent updates in Honor of Kings, like the changes in hero responsiveness and the puzzling matchmaking system, might be due to issues with these underlying mechanics. Don’t take it too personally; understanding the mechanics is more important than just practicing your skills.
Yin Hao: After running 30 kilometers this morning, I was starving, so I had a little something to tide me over. I'll drive to the office later.
Yin Hao: Jianguo, Xiaofeng and I just went over the details again. Tomorrow, we will finally carry out the plan we made in April! See you in Anji!
Chen Jie: Sorry, you were right at breakfast. I did forget last week. I'll take care of it tonight when I get back, and I'll pay attention to the water stains on the mirror.
Wang Lei: Yin Hao, the report has been signed and received. This week's work has been wrapped up smoothly!

Me: Honey, I talked to the master and the team leader during lunch today about wanting to do short videos, and they were very supportive, offering a lot of suggestions. I think I can give it a try now. It's all thanks to the inspiration from my chat with Jianguo last time.
Yin Hao: Auntie Chen, I'm almost at the hospital and brought lunch for you.
Chen Jie, regarding the delay in cleaning the living room, let's find a time to formally discuss the maintenance of our shared space.
